            "answer_text": "no,it is not necessary that friction always opposes motion. consider the following example of motion in which friction helps favourably in motion. suppose a small block is placed on the upper side of a big block. now big block is moved slowly in the forward direction. we will see that small block placed on the big block also moves in forward direction while we are moving only big block. in this example the direction of frictional (acting between down side of small block and upper side of big block) force is in the direction of motion which is enabling the small block to move in the direction of motion. ",
