            "answer_text": "No, friction can CAUSE motion, be in the same direction as motion. For example: Put a raft in the river. As the river flows past the raft, friction between the water molecules and the raft structure will speed up the raft to the same speed as the river current. Friction pushes the raft forward, giving it velocity. When you walk on the ground, your feet push against the ground backwards. Your feet don\u2019t slip because the sideways force on the ground is friction. By Newton\u2019s Third Law, the ground pushes FORWARD on your feet, causing you to move forward. So friction between the ground and your feet pushes forward, the same as the direction you are walking. ",
